  "topic": "How to manage and dealing with fake content on social media.",
  "opinion": "As a 44-year-old mechanic in Milan, self-employed and with three kids, I see fake content on social media like a faulty engine part—it can cause real damage if you don't spot it early. I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly for photography inspiration and keeping up with family, so I've learned to be practical about this. My curiosity helps me dig deeper, but my low openness means I stick to what I know works. First, I always check the source. If a post comes from an account I don't recognize or has a weird name, I'm skeptical—like when a customer brings in a car with aftermarket parts that don't fit right. I look for signs of reliability, such as official pages or trusted friends sharing it. Second, I use common sense. If something sounds too good or too shocking, it probably is. For example, I saw a post claiming a miracle fix for engine problems that would save thousands; I knew from my vocational training that real repairs take time and skill, so I ignored it. Third, I talk to people. With moderate agreeableness, I value others' opinions. I might ask my partner or fellow mechanics what they think before sharing anything. This helps avoid spreading misinformation, which can harm relationships or business. Finally, I limit my time online to stay focused. As a self-employed mechanic, I can't afford distractions, and fake content wastes energy. I teach my kids the same: think before you click, and trust your gut. It's about being responsible, just like maintaining a car—regular checks prevent bigger issues down the road.",
